d. They are being continued for the moment, but, obviously, once we are outside the European Union, our influence over that will be slightly diminished.     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Marcus Fysh (Yeovil) (Con)       Share       Does my right hon. Friend agree that the upcoming negotiation on leaving the EU presents a huge opportunity to redouble our efforts at co-operation with our EU friends and allies? What plans does he have to support UK defence industries and cross-border investments, such as those in helicopter manufacturing in Yeovil?     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Michael Fallon       Share       We will continue the co-operation that I have already set out—our co-operation with France under the Lancaster House treaty, and the growing co-operation we have with Germany and, indeed, with other European countries. Our recent strategic defence review is international by design and prioritises working more closely with our allies. European companies that are invested here see a rising defence budget, and we hope they will continue to invest here and to compete for the various tenders we are making available.     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.     Liz Kendall (Leicester West) (Lab)       Share       Our military alliances rely on strong diplomatic ties, especially with our European neighbours. What steps is the Secretary of State taking to ensure our Brexit negotiations do not sour these relationships and weaken our alliances?     Share          The edit just sent has not been saved.  The following error was returned:     This content has already been edited and is awaiting review.    